				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>If you've watched my lesson '<a title="Simple Shapes on the bass #2" href="http://scottsbasslessons.com/bass-lines-grooves/shapes-on-bass-2.html">Using Simple Shapes on the Bass #2</a>', perhaps you remember that it dealt with those 'sexy notes' that have a special flavor to them, that kinda<a href="http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/beginners/bass-tip-2-ear-training.html"> surprise our ear</a>, but in a nice way, well... at least for most of us.</p>
<p>In this new bass lesson, I'm showing you a very simple bass lick that does exactly that: the reason why it sounds so good is that it adds an element of surprise --that will probably get you a lot of 'wows' by the way!</p>
<p>The surprise comes from the fact that it includes a lot of notes that don't 'fit' in the expected harmony: most of the notes are not directly related to the G minor chord that we're playing over. As a result, there's a 'tension and release' effect that makes us feel good. Well, check out for yourself! ;)</p>
